  <static seed="1176" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/multiplyRationalExpressions10.pg">
    <statement><p>Select all correct equations:</p>
<p><var form="checkboxes">
<li>
<p><m>-\frac{x}{y} = \frac{-x}{-y}</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>3 \cdot \frac{x}{y} = \frac{3 x}{3 y}</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>3 \cdot \frac{x}{y} = \frac{x}{3 y}</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>-\frac{x}{y} = \frac{x}{-y}</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>3 \cdot \frac{x}{y} = \frac{3 x}{y}</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>-\frac{x}{y} = \frac{-x}{y}</m></p>
</li>
</var></p>
</statement>
    <solution><p>The correct answer is DEF.</p>
<p>Here is the correct way to do fraction multiplication:</p>
<p><m>3 \cdot \frac{x}{y} = \frac{3}{1} \cdot \frac{x}{y} = \frac{3 x}{y}</m></p>
<p>When a negative symbol is in front of a fraction, we can do:</p>
<p><m>-\frac{x}{y} = \frac{-x}{y}</m> (correct)</p>
<p><m>-\frac{x}{y} = \frac{x}{-y}</m> (correct)</p>
<p>We cannot do:</p>
<p><m>-\frac{x}{y} = \frac{-x}{-y}</m> (incorrect)</p>
<p>This is because <m>-\frac{6}{3} = \frac{-6}{3} = \frac{6}{-3} = -2</m>, but <m>-\frac{6}{3} \ne \frac{-6}{-3}</m>.</p>
<p>To summarize, when there is a negative symbol in front of a fraction, we could move it to the numerator or denominator, but may not change both the numerator and denominator to negative.</p>
</solution>
